1
0:00:35,660 --> 0:00:38,080
遥远的北方
In the far north,

2
0:00:38,080 --> 0:00:41,240
历经三个月黑暗寒冬之后
after three dark months of winter.

3
0:00:47,400 --> 0:00:49,520
整个世界都在悄然等待
a world is waiting

4
0:00:52,560 --> 0:00:54,800
那一缕春的阳光
..for a trigger.

5
0:00:57,080 --> 0:00:59,760
将其唤醒
The sunshine of spring.

6
0:01:11,320 --> 0:01:14,760
首先回应的是海星
Starfish are the first to respond.

7
0:01:26,400 --> 0:01:29,280
它们奔赴制高点
They race for the highest point...

8
0:01:31,760 --> 0:01:34,280
利用其管足
and sensing changes in the water,

9
0:01:34,280 --> 0:01:36,840
察觉到了水温的变化
with the tips of their tube feet...

10
0:01:39,240 --> 0:01:40,720
它们开始产卵
they spawn.

11
0:01:55,720 --> 0:01:58,000
海参
Sea cucumbers,

12
0:01:58,000 --> 0:02:00,440
原本只露出个嘴巴的它们
with only their mouths exposed,

13
0:02:00,440 --> 0:02:02,280
现在也探出了头
now emerge.

14
0:02:12,600 --> 0:02:15,800
对着海星的卵大快朵颐
They collect as many starfish eggs as they can.

15
0:02:29,720 --> 0:02:34,280
依靠那十只手 还真能吃下不少
Which is quite a lot, when you've got ten arms.

16
0:02:45,280 --> 0:02:48,800
现在海笔也冒出头 想分享大自然的馈赠
Now sea pens rise up to claim a share.

17
0:02:59,160 --> 0:03:03,800
在此年度盛宴上 这里的生物必须努力加餐
The creatures here must grab what they can of this annual banquet.

18
0:03:08,200 --> 0:03:13,520
因为阳光同样预示着一场巨大变革的到来
For the light has also set in motion the greatest transformation of all.

19
0:03:17,840 --> 0:03:20,280
大型褐藻 一种海洋藻类
Fronds of kelp, a marine alga,

20
0:03:20,280 --> 0:03:22,240
拔地而起
rise towards the surface,

21
0:03:22,240 --> 0:03:25,120
它们的气囊协助其向上生长
lifted by their gas-filled bladders.

22
0:03:37,040 --> 0:03:40,920
不久 一片"海底森林"便成形
Soon, a marine forest has materialised...

23
0:03:45,320 --> 0:03:48,720
各种生物在此大量繁衍
teeming with life of all kinds.

24
0:03:53,160 --> 0:03:57,360
绿色海洋是所有水域中最丰饶多产
These green seas are some of the most productive,

25
0:03:57,360 --> 0:04:01,610
而又竞争激烈的
but fiercely competitive, waters in all the oceans.

26
0:04:19,520 --> 0:04:21,720
非洲的最南端
The southern tip of Africa.

27
0:04:24,560 --> 0:04:28,920
两大洋在这里交汇
Here, two great oceans collide.

28
0:04:38,830 --> 0:04:43,200
在浅水区 营养丰富的洋流
In the shallows, fed by rich currents,

29
0:04:43,200 --> 0:04:46,240
滋养了茂盛的海藻林
are bountiful forests of kelp.

30
0:04:59,560 --> 0:05:04,720
几乎只能看见虹吸管一张一合的
Barely visible except for the pulsating siphon through which it breathes,

31
0:05:05,180 --> 0:05:06,600
是一只普通章鱼
a common octopus,

32
0:05:06,600 --> 0:05:08,840
伺机捕捉经过的猎物
waiting for prey to pass by.

33
0:05:13,840 --> 0:05:16,080
一只螃蟹就很不错
A crab will do.

34
0:05:22,440 --> 0:05:25,290
章鱼动身去追赶螃蟹
The octopus sets off in pursuit.

35
0:05:57,280 --> 0:05:59,400
之后潜伏起来
And then lurks.

36
0:06:00,200 --> 0:06:03,360
带着狩猎者与生俱来的沉着
with the patience of an ambush hunter.

37
0:06:28,240 --> 0:06:31,320
但好望角这片海域也同时
But the octopus shares the Cape waters

38
0:06:31,320 --> 0:06:34,880
汇聚了大量其它的捕食者
with a great concentration of other predators.

39
0:06:42,190 --> 0:06:44,000
海狗
Fur seals.

40
0:06:45,560 --> 0:06:47,000
和鲨鱼
and sharks.

41
0:06:50,760 --> 0:06:52,480
而它们的菜谱上都写了章鱼
They all eat octopus.

42
0:06:54,160 --> 0:06:56,040
只要能碰上
if they can find one.

43
0:07:04,720 --> 0:07:07,200
睡袍鲨则是
And pyjama sharks are experts

44
0:07:09,360 --> 0:07:11,960
下层水域的捕猎能手
at hunting in the undergrowth.

45
0:07:19,920 --> 0:07:21,800
是时候该躲起来了
Time to disappear.

46
0:07:28,920 --> 0:07:31,160
但这些皮肤坚硬的小鲨鱼
But these tough-skinned little sharks

47
0:07:31,160 --> 0:07:34,960
体型恰好可以深入裂缝中
are small enough to reach deep into crevices.

48
0:07:53,880 --> 0:07:57,240
但是章鱼可不会轻易认输
But the octopus is far from finished.

49
0:07:59,640 --> 0:08:03,560
它把触角滑进鲨鱼的鳃里
She slips her tentacles into the shark's gills.

50
0:08:04,920 --> 0:08:07,200
阻止其呼吸
That prevents the shark from breathing.

51
0:08:11,320 --> 0:08:14,120
最终后者不得不放弃
So, the shark has to let go.

52
0:08:25,640 --> 0:08:28,680
当章鱼无处藏匿极为脆弱时
When caught out in the open, and vulnerable,

53
0:08:28,680 --> 0:08:32,560
同样可以做出一些令人惊讶
this octopus does something truly extraordinary.

54
0:08:34,000 --> 0:08:36,840
闻所未闻的举动
and never recorded before.

55
0:08:47,160 --> 0:08:49,240
它做了一个贝壳盔甲
She disguises herself

56
0:08:51,800 --> 0:08:54,360
来伪装自己
with a protective armour of shells.

57
0:08:59,480 --> 0:09:03,720
她就躲避在敌人的视线之下
She's hiding...in plain sight.

58
0:09:14,120 --> 0:09:17,120
鲨鱼可以察觉到猎物
The shark can sense its prey

59
0:09:30,280 --> 0:09:32,440
但是贝壳迷惑了它
but the shells confuse it.

60
0:09:39,240 --> 0:09:42,060
在一个满是饥饿猎食者的森林里
In a forest full of hungry mouths,

61
0:09:42,860 --> 0:09:46,560
章鱼因它卓越的智慧而幸存
superior wits allow this octopus to stay alive.

62
0:09:58,330 --> 0:10:03,720
海藻森林在全世界季节性海域中繁荣生长
Forests of kelp flourish in seasonal waters around the globe...

63
0:10:07,800 --> 0:10:10,960
尤其是北美的太平洋沿岸
particularly along the Pacific Coast of North America.

64
0:10:19,520 --> 0:10:22,200
在这里 海藻森林中
Here, the biggest kelps of all

65
0:10:22,200 --> 0:10:24,160
生长着最大的藻类
grow in vast forests,

66
0:10:24,160 --> 0:10:27,280
可以延伸到几百英里之外
stretching for hundreds of miles.

67
0:10:32,240 --> 0:10:35,480
一些地区 那些巨藻
In some places, the giant fronds

68
0:10:35,480 --> 0:10:38,520
可以长到60米
rise up to 60 metres tall.

69
0:10:44,440 --> 0:10:48,360
茂盛的丛林中 生物繁多
The thickets they create are crowded with life.

70
0:10:56,520 --> 0:11:01,560
在这里 空间和食物的竞争异常激烈
Competition here, for space and food, is intense.

71
0:11:14,520 --> 0:11:18,760
这对于美国红雀来说可是个大难题
A challenging problem for the Garibaldi fish.

72
0:11:25,120 --> 0:11:28,080
它仔细照料自己的海藻地
He tends to his patch of seaweed,

73
0:11:28,080 --> 0:11:31,040
里面充满了它爱吃的小生物
filled with tiny creatures that he eats.

74
0:11:39,920 --> 0:11:44,000
和大多数农民一样 他一天到晚辛勤劳动
As with most farmers, his work never ends.

75
0:11:49,200 --> 0:11:52,280
它把海螺和其他一些
He removes snails and any other grazers

76
0:11:52,280 --> 0:11:54,560
吃他海藻的动物赶走
that come to eat his algae

77
0:12:13,120 --> 0:12:15,520
不管对方有多庞大
no matter how big they are.

78
0:12:25,480 --> 0:12:29,400
它必须处理所有的"害虫"
He has to deal with pests of all kinds.

79
0:12:32,040 --> 0:12:34,520
这是最难处理的家伙
This can be the worst of them -

80
0:12:34,520 --> 0:12:39,160
海胆会把岩石上的海藻刮得一干二净
sea urchins that can scrape off every vestige of algae from a rock.

81
0:12:40,600 --> 0:12:42,960
它们的刺像针一样锋利
Its spines are needle-sharp.

82
0:12:46,160 --> 0:12:48,880
雀鲷必须把它移走
Somehow, the GaribaldI must remove it.

83
0:13:02,920 --> 0:13:05,080
但问题是
But the problem with sea urchins

84
0:13:10,520 --> 0:13:13,200
海胆会不停的聚集过来
is that they just keep coming.

85
0:13:28,200 --> 0:13:33,200
当日渐西斜 夜晚来临 小雀鲷不得不停下
When evening arrives and the light fades, he has to stop.

86
0:13:33,200 --> 0:13:36,960
它不仅需要休息 还需要躲藏
He not only needs a rest, he needs to hide.

87
0:13:41,280 --> 0:13:45,960
因为在晚上 捕猎者会穿梭在森林中觅食
Because at night, predators prowl through these forests.

88
0:13:50,200 --> 0:13:52,240
电鳐
A torpedo ray,

89
0:13:52,240 --> 0:13:56,920
能用45伏特的电压 把猎物电晕
capable of stunning its victim with 45 volts of electricity.

90
0:14:08,920 --> 0:14:10,840
当雀鲷躲起来时
While the Garibaldi hides...

91
0:14:12,480 --> 0:14:15,160
海胆又能肆无忌惮的吃海藻了
the urchins can feed without interruption.

92
0:14:24,880 --> 0:14:27,240
白天来临
The light returns...

93
0:14:30,880 --> 0:14:34,760
它发现自己的农田又一次遭到破坏
and he finds his farm is once again under attack.

94
0:14:51,040 --> 0:14:53,160
海胆就像蝗虫
Urchins, like locusts,

95
0:14:53,160 --> 0:14:56,360
总是蜂拥而至
have the ability to swarm.

96
0:15:02,960 --> 0:15:06,880
这会是一个大灾难 不仅是对雀鲷来说
And this can be disastrous, not just for the Garibaldi,

97
0:15:06,880 --> 0:15:10,040
更是对整个海藻森林
but for the kelp forest itself.

98
0:15:22,360 --> 0:15:25,960
现在所有的植物都遭到破坏
All the vegetation is now under attack.

99
0:15:54,440 --> 0:15:57,320
海胆在森林里
The urchins move through the forest,

100
0:15:57,320 --> 0:16:00,000
肆虐横行
cutting through the kelp fronds

101
0:16:00,000 --> 0:16:02,840
留下一片狼藉
and leaving behind vast barrens.

102
0:16:06,920 --> 0:16:10,360
这些海胆军团曾袭击过
These urchin armies have felled many kelp forests

103
0:16:10,360 --> 0:16:13,200
北美洲太平洋沿岸的许多海藻森林
along the Pacific Coast of North America.

104
0:16:20,160 --> 0:16:22,760
但是救兵顷刻将至
But help is at hand.

105
0:16:42,640 --> 0:16:44,360
海獭
Sea otters.

106
0:16:48,800 --> 0:16:53,600
其他水獭大多常年生活在陆地上
All other kinds of otters spend much of their lives on land,

107
0:16:53,600 --> 0:16:56,560
但海獭却很少离开水
but sea otters rarely leave the water.

108
0:17:00,280 --> 0:17:04,800
一开始 新生的小海獭还不怎么会游泳
At first, a newly-born pup is not a very good swimmer,

109
0:17:04,800 --> 0:17:09,520
水獭妈妈会花数个小时帮宝宝梳理毛发 好让它浮起来
so its mother spends hours grooming its fur to make it buoyant.

110
0:17:16,280 --> 0:17:20,480
水獭妈妈为了给孩子喂奶 并保持自身体温
But to provide her youngster with milk and keep herself warm,

111
0:17:20,480 --> 0:17:24,640
每天必须吃掉相当于其体重30%的食物
she must eat up to 30% of her body weight every day.

112
0:17:43,960 --> 0:17:47,120
贝类是她的家常菜
She does that by eating shellfish.

113
0:17:52,240 --> 0:17:56,760
而海胆则是海獭的最爱
And urchins are among a sea otter's favourite delicacies.

114
0:18:15,400 --> 0:18:20,000
过去 人们为了海獭的毛皮对其肆意捕杀
In the past, sea otters were hunted so intensively for their fur

115
0:18:20,000 --> 0:18:22,240
使它们濒临灭绝
that they came close to extinction.

116
0:18:27,040 --> 0:18:33,760
海獭数量减少 海藻森林则被海胆占领 留下大片荒凉
With them gone, many kelp forests were replaced with urchin barrens.

117
0:18:43,200 --> 0:18:45,920
现在 海獭被保护起来
Today, sea otters are protected...

118
0:18:49,400 --> 0:18:52,080
随着它们数量的缓慢回升
and as their numbers slowly return,

119
0:18:52,080 --> 0:18:55,240
许多海藻森林也在恢复
many of the kelp forests are recovering, too.

120
0:19:11,640 --> 0:19:13,520
现在 一些偏远地区
Now, in some remote places,

121
0:19:13,520 --> 0:19:15,360
生活着大量海獭
sea otters are so numerous

122
0:19:15,360 --> 0:19:19,040
它们汇聚成一个个巨型筏子
they assemble in huge rafts...

123
0:19:23,040 --> 0:19:27,040
类似的场景已经上百年未曾见过
something that hasn't been seen for over a century.

124
0:20:09,370 --> 0:20:12,560
在澳洲阳光充足的浅水区
In the sun-drenched shallows off Australia...

125
0:20:13,960 --> 0:20:19,040
生长的不是海藻 而是海上唯一的开花植物
kelp is replaced by the sea's only flowering plants,

126
0:20:19,040 --> 0:20:21,160
海草
sea grass.

127
0:20:29,000 --> 0:20:32,680
最广阔的海洋草地
The most extensive of these marine grasslands

128
0:20:32,680 --> 0:20:36,080
能衍延伸3000多平方英里
can stretch for over 3,000 square miles.

129
0:20:50,040 --> 0:20:54,000
整片热带区域 都由虎鲨巡逻着
All across the tropics, they're patrolled by tiger sharks.

130
0:20:58,720 --> 0:21:01,720
它们能长到5米长
They can grow up to five metres in length...

131
0:21:08,200 --> 0:21:10,840
拥有可以撕开猎物的强大双颚
and have powerful crushing jaws.

132
0:21:19,680 --> 0:21:22,280
绿海龟是它们的食物
Green turtles are their prey.

133
0:21:27,160 --> 0:21:31,440
海龟几乎完全以海草为生
The turtles feed almost entirely on sea grass.

134
0:21:33,120 --> 0:21:37,960
一只海龟每天能消耗2公斤海草
A single one can consume up to two kilos of it in a day.

135
0:21:54,800 --> 0:21:56,520
但它们从来不得安生
But they can never rest easy.

136
0:22:07,160 --> 0:22:11,800
健康的海龟会避开接近的鲨鱼
Healthy turtles will keep well away from an approaching shark.

137
0:22:26,040 --> 0:22:29,680
通过使海龟的不停移动
And just by keeping the turtles on the move,

138
0:22:29,680 --> 0:22:34,640
鲨鱼便防止了海草被过度破坏
the sharks prevent any one patch of sea grass from being overgrazed.

139
0:22:40,760 --> 0:22:43,040
这对大家都有利
And that has benefits for us all.

140
0:22:51,920 --> 0:22:55,200
与同面积的热带雨林相比
A patch of sea grass can absorb and store

141
0:22:55,200 --> 0:22:58,800
海草能吸收并储存
35 times as much carbon dioxide

142
0:22:58,800 --> 0:23:02,160
雨林35倍的二氧化碳
as the same area of a rainforest.

143
0:23:07,480 --> 0:23:09,980
所以 这片草甸与鲨鱼们
So, the prairies and their sharks

144
0:23:10,010 --> 0:23:14,400
在对抗全球变暖的斗争中成了盟友
are surprising allies in the fight against a warming climate.

145
0:23:24,200 --> 0:23:27,080
绿海图存的斗争
The struggle to survive in our green seas

146
0:23:27,080 --> 0:23:29,480
可能带来尤为深远的影响
can have far-reaching consequences.

147
0:23:31,960 --> 0:23:38,200
每年 澳洲的这片特殊草原 都在变化
Once a year, one particular meadow in Australia is transformed.

148
0:23:45,280 --> 0:23:48,800
在冬季的首个满月前后
Around the first full moon of winter,

149
0:23:48,800 --> 0:23:51,000
一支军队逐渐集结
an army materialises.

150
0:23:54,640 --> 0:23:56,490
蜘蛛蟹
Spider crabs.

151
0:24:04,480 --> 0:24:07,600
过去的一年里 他们都在深海区觅食
For the past year, they've been feeding in deeper waters.

152
0:24:18,430 --> 0:24:22,720
现在 他们要穿过这片海上草原
Now they march across the sea-grass plains.

153
0:24:40,680 --> 0:24:43,640
数量可达几十万
Hundreds of thousands of them.

154
0:24:51,840 --> 0:24:53,560
一个个叠在一起
They clamber over one another...

155
0:25:00,160 --> 0:25:02,720
形成一个巨大的山丘
creating great mounds...

156
0:25:08,160 --> 0:25:10,840
绵延近百米
nearly 100 metres long.

157
0:25:14,240 --> 0:25:18,880
它们不是在寻找配偶 也不是在产卵
They're not seeking mates, neither are they laying eggs.

158
0:25:18,880 --> 0:25:21,800
而是为了
They have come here in order...

159
0:25:21,800 --> 0:25:23,240
成长
to grow.

160
0:25:25,720 --> 0:25:27,200
像其他螃蟹一样
Like all crabs,

161
0:25:27,200 --> 0:25:28,960
他们的身体被封闭在
their bodies are enclosed

162
0:25:28,960 --> 0:25:31,800
坚硬 不能伸缩的壳里面
in a hard, un-expandable shell.

163
0:25:34,360 --> 0:25:37,560
所以 为了成长 必须打破硬壳
So, to grow, they have to break out of it...

164
0:25:47,680 --> 0:25:53,640
这样才能使硬壳之下的柔软新壳长大
and that allows the soft one that has developed beneath to expand.

165
0:26:01,320 --> 0:26:03,920
新壳需要数天才能变硬
It will take days for the new shell to harden.

166
0:26:16,520 --> 0:26:20,040
这时 它们的腿疲软无力 不能灵活行动
Its legs are so limp that they won't work properly.

167
0:26:24,280 --> 0:26:28,440
蜘蛛蟹失去保护外壳 极为脆弱
The crab is unprotected and in great danger.

168
0:26:37,360 --> 0:26:39,520
刺魟
A smooth stingray.

169
0:26:42,800 --> 0:26:45,120
体型巨大 长达四米
It's huge - about four metres long.

170
0:26:47,760 --> 0:26:51,560
它想抓住只柔软 刚蜕壳的蜘蛛蟹
It wants a soft, freshly-moulted crab

171
0:26:51,560 --> 0:26:53,680
这种食物更好下口
that will be easier to eat.

172
0:27:14,920 --> 0:27:17,480
蜘蛛蟹努力 聚到一起
The crabs try to stick together.

173
0:27:25,280 --> 0:27:27,760
但现在被刺魟分散开
But now, disturbed by the ray,

174
0:27:27,760 --> 0:27:29,240
四散奔逃
they're scattering.

175
0:27:35,160 --> 0:27:37,400
一只刚蜕壳的蜘蛛蟹
A newly-moulted crab

176
0:27:37,400 --> 0:27:40,440
因为太虚弱 跟不上群体
is too weak to keep up with the crowd.

177
0:27:55,120 --> 0:27:58,640
最安全的地方是蟹群的中央
The safest place is right in the middle of the pile.

178
0:28:00,480 --> 0:28:03,760
这也是它们聚集在一起的原因
That is why they have all assembled here.

179
0:28:12,160 --> 0:28:14,680
数量越多 越安全
There is safety in numbers.

180
0:28:30,480 --> 0:28:33,280
绝大多数的蜘蛛蟹能够逃脱
The vast majority of the crabs escape...

181
0:28:34,360 --> 0:28:36,080
几天过后
and within the next few days,

182
0:28:36,080 --> 0:28:38,920
它们就准备回归深海
they will be ready to return to the depths

183
0:28:38,920 --> 0:28:43,200
重新开始流浪般的孤独觅食
and resume their lonely wanderings in search of food.

184
0:28:55,120 --> 0:28:57,560
这不是一片墓地
This is no graveyard...

185
0:29:00,080 --> 0:29:05,480
而是十万多只蜘蛛蟹蜕壳成功的胜利标志
..but the triumph of a 100,000 crabs successfully moulted.

186
0:29:30,600 --> 0:29:33,680
在澳大利亚南部的绿色海洋
The green seas of Southern Australia

187
0:29:33,680 --> 0:29:37,200
类似壮观的聚集十分多
are particularly rich in such spectacular assemblies...

188
0:29:41,000 --> 0:29:43,600
但是大多数物种聚集起来
..but most of the creatures come together

189
0:29:43,600 --> 0:29:45,760
是为了一件截然不同的事情
for a very different reason.

190
0:29:47,800 --> 0:29:49,600
交配繁殖
To breed.

191
0:29:53,600 --> 0:29:55,960
澳大利亚巨型乌贼
The giant cuttlefish,

192
0:29:56,560 --> 0:29:58,560
体型最大的乌贼
the largest of all cuttlefish.

193
0:30:06,000 --> 0:30:08,880
生命周期只有一到两年
They live for just one or two years.

194
0:30:14,640 --> 0:30:18,520
随着澳大利亚的夏季即将结束
Now, as the Australian summer draws to an end,

195
0:30:18,520 --> 0:30:21,280
它们还有最后一件事情需要完成
they have one last act to complete.

196
0:30:25,240 --> 0:30:26,920
求偶
To find a mate.

197
0:30:32,200 --> 0:30:35,440
在这一个海湾里 就有超过10万只雄性乌贼
But there are over 100,000 males,

198
0:30:35,440 --> 0:30:39,560
准备争夺即将到来的雌性乌贼
competing for the arriving females in this one bay.

199
0:30:45,920 --> 0:30:49,600
他们之中有一个名副其实的歌利亚
Among them a giant - a true Goliath.

200
0:30:49,600 --> 0:30:53,000
体重大概有10公斤
He probably weighs about ten kilos.

201
0:30:55,720 --> 0:30:59,240
皮肤上色彩绚丽的带状花纹
Bands of colour sweep across his skin.

202
0:30:59,240 --> 0:31:01,120
正是乌贼的交流方式
That's how cuttlefish communicate.

203
0:31:21,050 --> 0:31:24,650
这只体型较小的雄性乌贼显然难以与之匹敌
This smaller male couldn't possibly take him on.

204
0:31:34,560 --> 0:31:37,600
在歌利亚身旁 其庇护之下
Beside Goliath, and under his protection,

205
0:31:37,600 --> 0:31:40,160
一只雌性乌贼刚刚与它交配完
a female who has just mated with him.

206
0:31:43,560 --> 0:31:46,560
但其它竞争者仍旧蠢蠢欲动
But other rivals are still interested.

207
0:31:50,400 --> 0:31:53,790
看来小个头的雄性是毫无胜算的
It seems a small male wouldn't stand a chance.

208
0:31:55,840 --> 0:31:58,600
雌性乌贼朝着歌利亚一侧的身体上
The female is now displaying a white stripe

209
0:31:58,600 --> 0:32:01,040
显出了白色条纹
along her side nearest Goliath.

210
0:32:04,440 --> 0:32:07,800
这是个明显的信号 她不想与其交配了
It's a clear signal that she no longer wants to mate with him.

211
0:32:13,400 --> 0:32:16,880
这条小型雄乌贼又重拾了希望
It's all the encouragement that the little male needs.

212
0:32:39,720 --> 0:32:42,200
它打算耍个花招
He's going to have to use trickery.

213
0:32:57,120 --> 0:33:00,000
把自己表皮的颜色变暗
He tones down his colours

214
0:33:00,000 --> 0:33:02,720
蜷缩起它的触手
and tucks in his arms.

215
0:33:04,400 --> 0:33:07,600
他模仿成雌性乌贼大小
He's just the right size to mimic a female.

216
0:33:18,880 --> 0:33:20,960
歌利亚上当了
Goliath is deceived.

217
0:33:23,760 --> 0:33:27,560
这头小型雄性乌贼的身上也出现了白色条纹
The small male now displays a white stripe,

218
0:33:27,560 --> 0:33:30,920
就像真正的雌性一样  这是为了阻止歌利亚靠近自己
just like the real female, to deter his advances.

219
0:33:37,080 --> 0:33:38,960
它溜到她身边
He slips beside her...

220
0:33:42,080 --> 0:33:43,800
然后和她交配
..and they mate.

221
0:33:54,940 --> 0:33:57,360
通过与多个伴侣交配
By mating with multiple partners...

222
0:33:59,000 --> 0:34:03,600
雌性乌贼能够最大程度上确保其后代遗传基因的多样性
..the female ensures the greatest genetic diversity for her young.

223
0:34:09,720 --> 0:34:12,380
这个狡猾的雄性离开了
The sneaky male leaves,

224
0:34:12,800 --> 0:34:15,640
他已完成了终极目标
his final act complete.

225
0:34:20,160 --> 0:34:23,680
所以 即使是在巨型乌贼当中
So, even among giant cuttlefish, it seems...

226
0:34:26,440 --> 0:34:28,840
个头也并不总是能决定一切
..it's not all about size.

227
0:34:39,040 --> 0:34:43,400
另一些居住在这片澳大利亚绿色海草里的雄性生物
Other males in these Australian green pastures,

228
0:34:43,400 --> 0:34:46,840
则要为它们的后代承担更重大的责任
take greater responsibility for their young.

229
0:34:55,320 --> 0:34:58,160
一只草海龙
A weedy sea dragon.

230
0:35:05,000 --> 0:35:09,400
这是只雄性海龙 它正身负重任
This is a male and he's carrying a precious cargo.

231
0:35:11,200 --> 0:35:13,440
在与雌性进行交配时
While mating with the female,

232
0:35:13,440 --> 0:35:17,160
他会收集雌性所产的卵 并将它们附在自己身体下部
he collected the eggs and attached them to his underside.

233
0:35:23,400 --> 0:35:26,800
现在 他正要离开这片海草丛
Now, he's leaving these seaweed thickets...

234
0:35:29,390 --> 0:35:32,000
前往更开阔的水域
..and travelling into more open waters

235
0:35:32,000 --> 0:35:35,280
在那里几乎无处藏身
where elaborate camouflage is less effective.

236
0:35:43,640 --> 0:35:46,280
并且有诸多的捕食者
And there are many predators out here.

237
0:36:07,960 --> 0:36:12,280
而这便是海龙爸爸不惜以身犯险的理由
And this is what the fathers risk their lives for.

238
0:36:20,460 --> 0:36:22,880
多如烟云般的小虾
Dense clouds of minute shrimp.

239
0:36:27,360 --> 0:36:32,920
糠虾 海龙最喜欢的食物之一
Mysids, one of a sea dragon's favourite foods.

240
0:36:43,480 --> 0:36:46,200
这也引来了其它的海龙
They're drawing other sea dragons out here, too.

241
0:37:09,040 --> 0:37:13,120
终于 小家伙们该出世了
Finally, it's time for the young to break free.

242
0:37:14,560 --> 0:37:17,900
但水藻覆满了这些正在成长的卵
But algae has grown over these developing eggs...

243
0:37:19,880 --> 0:37:21,720
这会让它们有窒息的风险
..and it risks smothering them.

244
0:37:26,560 --> 0:37:29,440
然而 小宝宝们还是顺利降生
Nonetheless, the babies are emerging.

245
0:37:40,560 --> 0:37:42,520
它们成功地孵化了
They've hatched successfully.

246
0:37:53,840 --> 0:37:56,920
父亲们回到了巨大的海藻丛中
The fathers return to the tangle of kelp,

247
0:37:56,920 --> 0:37:58,920
在那里可以很好地隐藏自己
where they're virtually invisible...

248
0:38:05,400 --> 0:38:07,520
年幼的海龙继续留在那
..while the young remain out here.

249
0:38:11,680 --> 0:38:13,820
被钟爱的食物所环绕
But they will grow quickly,

250
0:38:14,280 --> 0:38:17,640
它们很快便能长大
surrounded as they are by their ideal food.

251
0:38:28,280 --> 0:38:31,480
为数众多的小型鱼类
Vast numbers of the oceans' young fish

252
0:38:31,480 --> 0:38:34,360
早期都生活在这片绿色海洋里
start their lives in the green seas.

253
0:38:39,960 --> 0:38:45,880
而红树林当属其中最为富饶的水域
One of the richest nurseries of all are the mangrove forests.

254
0:38:50,480 --> 0:38:53,560
沿着热带地区海岸线边缘生长
Fringing the coastline of the tropics,

255
0:38:53,560 --> 0:38:57,680
它们在陆地与海洋之间建立了一个天然的保护屏障
they form a natural protective barrier between land and sea...

256
0:38:59,600 --> 0:39:03,120
同时也是世界上最丰富多产的森林
..and are some of the world's most productive forests.

257
0:39:15,960 --> 0:39:19,080
在水面之下 拱状的树根
Below the water, their arching aerial roots

258
0:39:19,080 --> 0:39:21,240
赋予他们扎实的底子
give them a firm footing.

259
0:39:32,480 --> 0:39:35,320
这里能够为幼鱼提供充足的食物
Here, there's abundant food for baby fish.

260
0:39:40,840 --> 0:39:44,320
盘根错节保护它们不受大型鱼类
While the tangled roots protect them from bigger fish

261
0:39:44,320 --> 0:39:47,760
以及其他捕食者们的纠缠
and other predators that haunt the channels.

262
0:40:18,760 --> 0:40:21,070
但在澳大利亚北部
But in Northern Australia,

263
0:40:21,240 --> 0:40:23,720
随着潮水退去
with the receding tide...

264
0:40:25,560 --> 0:40:29,520
小型鱼类不得不离开它们的庇护所
..the little fish are forced to leave their shelter.

265
0:40:34,440 --> 0:40:36,960
现在 它们变得十分脆弱
And now, they are vulnerable.

266
0:41:22,280 --> 0:41:26,080
这是绿色海洋里最为致命的杀手
It's the most deadly assassin in the green seas.

267
0:41:34,040 --> 0:41:36,600
斑马纹螳螂虾
The zebra mantis shrimp,

268
0:41:37,310 --> 0:41:40,640
一只雄性虾蛄 大约四十厘米长
a male, almost 40 centimetres long.

269
0:41:57,920 --> 0:42:00,600
但它捕猎并不只是为了自己
But he's not hunting just for himself.

270
0:42:05,920 --> 0:42:09,280
它在为自己的伴侣搜集食物
He's collecting food for his mate.

271
0:42:10,760 --> 0:42:14,080
双方在一起已经近二十年了
She may have been his partner for 20 years.

272
0:42:22,040 --> 0:42:25,120
她依靠雄虾为自己带来食物
She relies on him to bring her food...

273
0:42:27,640 --> 0:42:31,000
这样她才能有力气生儿育女
..and puts her energy into her eggs instead.

274
0:42:36,000 --> 0:42:38,040
在这个食物充足的世界里
In a world so full of food,

275
0:42:38,040 --> 0:42:40,800
这种方法显得合情合理
this would seem a sensible strategy.

276
0:42:48,540 --> 0:42:50,640
但同时也极为冒险
But it's also a risky one.

277
0:43:16,140 --> 0:43:18,040
如果她的雄性伴侣消失不见
Were her male to disappear,

278
0:43:18,040 --> 0:43:20,240
她可能会饿死
she could starve.

279
0:43:28,040 --> 0:43:31,360
有什么东西引起了雄性虾蛄的注意
Something has caught this male's attention.

280
0:43:33,760 --> 0:43:36,360
也许是猎物令人无法抗拒的气味
Perhaps an irresistible odour...

281
0:43:38,120 --> 0:43:40,440
又或许是一声遥远的呼唤
..or a distant call.

282
0:43:42,800 --> 0:43:44,440
不管那是什么
Whatever the reason,

283
0:43:44,440 --> 0:43:47,320
这只雄性虾蛄都要离开自己的洞穴
a male will leave his burrow

284
0:43:47,320 --> 0:43:49,920
和它那约定终身的伴侣
and his lifelong mate.

285
0:43:58,360 --> 0:44:01,280
(前往)一个更大的洞穴
An even larger hole.

286
0:44:12,920 --> 0:44:15,040
雌性虾蛄在失去伴侣之后
Females who have lost their mates

287
0:44:15,040 --> 0:44:19,840
会发出求救信号 召唤新的伴侣
appear to send out distress signals to call in a new male.

288
0:44:26,000 --> 0:44:28,760
体型更大的雌性虾蛄会产更多的卵
A larger female will produce more eggs.

289
0:44:28,830 --> 0:44:33,000
如果和她交配 这只雄性虾蛄会有更多的后代
So by mating with her, he will father more offspring.

290
0:44:38,680 --> 0:44:42,320
但出轨是要付出代价的
But infidelity comes at a price.

291
0:44:45,760 --> 0:44:49,560
更大的伴侣其食欲自然也更大
A larger partner demands more food.

292
0:45:03,740 --> 0:45:07,040
海洋越是富饶 那里的竞争也就越激烈
The richer a sea, the greater the competition.

293
0:45:08,400 --> 0:45:10,600
而这里有一片绿色海洋
...and there is one green sea

294
0:45:10,600 --> 0:45:15,160
比其他所有海洋联合起来养育的生命还要多
that supports more life than all the rest combined.

295
0:45:17,920 --> 0:45:21,160
不同于红树林和海草原
Unlike the mangrove forests and the sea-grass prairies,

296
0:45:21,160 --> 0:45:24,400
它坐落在外海
its location is in the open seas

297
0:45:24,400 --> 0:45:27,920
时间短暂且不可预知
and only temporary and unpredictable.

298
0:45:32,440 --> 0:45:36,240
这片绿意不是来自于生根植物
This greenness comes not from rooted plants...

299
0:45:38,560 --> 0:45:41,280
而是来自成群的浮游生物
..but from clouds of floating ones.

300
0:45:51,240 --> 0:45:56,360
亿万浮游生物正在分裂繁殖
Billions of microscopic phytoplankton are proliferating.

301
0:46:01,820 --> 0:46:07,520
它们在为最盛大的宴会提供养料
And in such numbers that they fuel one of the greatest feasts of all.

302
0:46:16,800 --> 0:46:19,520
在美国太平洋海岸区外
Off America's Pacific Coast,

303
0:46:19,520 --> 0:46:23,960
几百只普通海豚正赶着赴宴
hundreds of common dolphins are rushing to a banquet.

304
0:46:33,720 --> 0:46:36,480
它们不是唯一赶去的生物
They're not the only ones homing in.

305
0:46:38,800 --> 0:46:40,680
海狮亦是如此
So are sea lions.

306
0:46:46,600 --> 0:46:50,800
它们要前往加利福尼亚州蒙特雷湾
They're heading for Monterey Bay, California,

307
0:46:50,800 --> 0:46:55,040
那里藻类植物繁茂 导致浮游生物
where algal blooms have caused an explosion

308
0:46:55,040 --> 0:46:57,600
呈爆炸式生长
in plankton feeders.

309
0:47:00,120 --> 0:47:03,440
凤尾鱼 百万雄军
Anchovies, millions of them.

310
0:47:10,240 --> 0:47:13,520
海豚把凤尾鱼赶向海水表面
The dolphins herd the anchovies towards the surface.

311
0:47:16,840 --> 0:47:21,000
海鸟和海狮从中占得便宜
Sea birds and sea lions take advantage of the shoal's appearance.

312
0:47:25,960 --> 0:47:29,800
大家都抢着在其他生物到来之前分一杯羹
It's a race to grab a share before others arrive.

313
0:47:49,280 --> 0:47:51,800
座头鲸
Humpback whales,

314
0:47:51,800 --> 0:47:54,000
共有好几百头
hundreds of them.

315
0:48:04,040 --> 0:48:06,200
每向上张开一次血盆大口
With every upward lunge,

316
0:48:06,200 --> 0:48:09,880
它们都能筛出100多公斤的鱼
they sieve out up to 100 kilos of fish.

317
0:48:26,720 --> 0:48:28,760
它们从最大的一场盛宴中
They're  claiming the biggest share

318
0:48:28,760 --> 0:48:32,640
拿走了最丰厚的一份
of one of the biggest feasts on Earth.

319
0:49:01,800 --> 0:49:04,640
这些微小的浮游生物至关重要
So crucial are these tiny plankton,

320
0:49:04,640 --> 0:49:08,640
因为几乎所有的海洋生物都赖以生存
that almost all marine life ultimately depends upon them.

321
0:49:19,120 --> 0:49:22,560
绿色的海洋 而非蓝色
It's the green seas, not the blue...

322
0:49:24,440 --> 0:49:29,560
才是世界海洋之中所有生命的基础
..that are the basis of almost all life in the world's oceans.

323
0:49:29,560 --> 0:49:31,560


324
0:50:18,560 --> 0:50:21,480
为了捕捉到海底森林的壮美景色
To capture the magnificence of the undersea forests

325
0:50:21,480 --> 0:50:24,300
以及生活在其中的令人惊奇的生物 
and the surprising creatures living here,

326
0:50:24,350 --> 0:50:28,960
蓝色星球Ⅱ的团队开发了一系列专业摄影器械
the Blue Planet II team have developed a series of specialist camera rigs.

327
0:50:36,200 --> 0:50:40,640
从巨型拱顶摄像机 可以在树冠层捕捉
From the mega-dome recording half-in-half-out shots

328
0:50:40,640 --> 0:50:42,760
一半水面一半水下的镜头
at the top of the towering canopy...

329
0:50:45,320 --> 0:50:48,160
到最先进的延时设备
..to state-of-the-art time-lapse equipment

330
0:50:48,160 --> 0:50:52,760
去发现海底森林里最隐秘的生命
that speeds up time to reveal the secret life of the forest floor.

331
0:51:12,240 --> 0:51:15,000
不过 在所有水下生命拍摄中
But, of all the creatures living in these forests,

332
0:51:15,000 --> 0:51:18,360
在南非好望角水域的取材
filming one in the waters off the Cape of South Africa

333
0:51:18,360 --> 0:51:20,680
被认作是最艰巨的挑战
was to prove the greatest challenge of all.

334
0:51:23,480 --> 0:51:27,000
自然学家克雷格 福斯特对那里最为神秘的居民
Naturalist Craig Foster has developed a fascination

335
0:51:27,000 --> 0:51:31,080
产生了浓厚兴趣 一只普通章鱼
for its most secretive resident, a common octopus.

336
0:51:37,280 --> 0:51:40,880
这片水域中生活着大概100种鲨鱼
There are almost 100 species of shark in these waters,

337
0:51:40,880 --> 0:51:42,840
但克雷格没有被吓倒
but that doesn't deter Craig,

338
0:51:42,840 --> 0:51:46,360
在过去的六年里 他每天清晨都到这里游泳
who's swum here every morning for the past six years.

339
0:51:53,960 --> 0:51:57,640
如果你能够找到这种极为微小的椭圆形空洞
When you find that really small, tiny, little oval hole,

340
0:51:57,640 --> 0:52:00,560
就说明它是被一只章鱼杀死的
then you know it's been killed by an octopus.

341
0:52:01,840 --> 0:52:03,920
如果你再仔细进行观察
And then if you look very, very carefully,

342
0:52:03,920 --> 0:52:07,400
就会发现它们经常在附近徘徊
they're often in the vicinity of that.

343
0:52:14,600 --> 0:52:17,760
克雷格见过这些章鱼的滑稽举动
Craig has witnessed the antics of these octopuses

344
0:52:17,760 --> 0:52:21,040
他很想把这种了不起的发现
and wants to share his remarkable discoveries

345
0:52:21,040 --> 0:52:23,600
与蓝色星球的摄影师罗杰 霍洛克斯分享
with Blue Planet cameraman Roger Horrocks.

346
0:52:32,120 --> 0:52:36,440
罗杰很快就被这些家伙鲜明的个性迷住了
Roger is immediately charmed by the strength of their personalities.

347
0:52:38,880 --> 0:52:43,240
看到这些生物都有着各自的特性真是相当令人惊讶
It's really been astounding to see how individual these characters are.

348
0:52:43,240 --> 0:52:46,800
每一只章鱼都展现出了不同的行为举止
The common octopus all display different behaviours.

349
0:52:48,560 --> 0:52:50,280
有些章鱼胆小如鼠
Some were extremely timid,

350
0:52:50,280 --> 0:52:52,360
有些则胆大包天
some were very, very bold,

351
0:52:52,360 --> 0:52:55,080
它们的个性多种多样 我非常喜欢它们
they have variety and it's really endeared me to them.

352
0:53:01,320 --> 0:53:03,880
摄影师不停拍摄各类章鱼 几周之后
After weeks of filming different individuals,

353
0:53:03,880 --> 0:53:05,800
他们终于遇见了一只章鱼
they finally meet one octopus

354
0:53:05,800 --> 0:53:09,000
她看起来并不害怕摄像机
that's not only seemingly unafraid of the camera,

355
0:53:09,000 --> 0:53:11,040
反倒愿意主动靠近
but willing to perform for it.

356
0:53:21,080 --> 0:53:23,080
她就直接这么过来了
She just came right up - whoop!

357
0:53:23,080 --> 0:53:26,320
然后直接穿过我两腿之间的三脚架
And then came right through underneath the tripod in between my legs.

358
0:53:26,640 --> 0:53:28,760
是吧 她很酷 很了不起
Yeah, that's cool, amazing.

359
0:53:28,760 --> 0:53:32,880
她很快就全盘接受了我们俩
She very quickly just completely accepted both of us.

360
0:53:32,880 --> 0:53:35,640
我们实际上已经做出了一些非常亲密的行为
So, we've actually been getting these really intimate behaviours.

361
0:53:35,680 --> 0:53:37,400
令人惊叹
It's amazing.

362
0:53:41,600 --> 0:53:43,600
我已经观察这只章鱼好几个月了
I've watched this octopus for many months,

363
0:53:43,600 --> 0:53:45,200
在水下她一直很信任我们
it's just trusting us in the water,

364
0:53:45,200 --> 0:53:48,680
她一直正常活动 这真是太棒了
carrying on with normal activity which is just so fantastic.

365
0:53:56,680 --> 0:54:01,440
几个月后 团队终于拍到了这只明星章鱼狩猎的情景
Months later, the team finally film their star octopus on the hunt.

366
0:54:18,040 --> 0:54:22,000
然而接下来 他们便发现占有这片海底深林的
But then discover the grave consequences of sharing the forest

367
0:54:22,000 --> 0:54:24,880
并不只有章鱼
with so many other predators -

368
0:54:24,880 --> 0:54:26,440
睡袍鲨
pyjama sharks.

369
0:54:27,960 --> 0:54:30,720
一般情况下 这种鲨鱼比大白鲨
Pound for pound, these sharks are far more brazen

370
0:54:30,720 --> 0:54:32,560
更为凶狠好斗
and aggressive than a Great White.

371
0:54:32,560 --> 0:54:34,720
它们就像导弹
They're like guided missiles.

372
0:54:34,830 --> 0:54:39,520
即使章鱼只留下一点点气味 睡袍鲨都能找到它
The slightest smell that octopus gives off, that shark will find it.

373
0:54:44,200 --> 0:54:46,880
这只睡袍鲨实际上已经抓住了那只章鱼
The pyjama shark actually got hold of the octopus

374
0:54:46,880 --> 0:54:49,680
我当时以为她肯定完了
and, I mean, I just assumed that was it.

375
0:54:52,800 --> 0:54:55,440
与她长时间相处后
After spending so much time with this animal,

376
0:54:55,440 --> 0:54:58,560
你很难真正无动于衷
it was just so difficult watching her get attacked.

377
0:55:04,910 --> 0:55:08,280
之后令他们意想不到的是 她居然反击了
Then, to their amazement, she fights back!

378
0:55:14,080 --> 0:55:15,800
她伸出自己的触手
She put her tentacles down,

379
0:55:15,800 --> 0:55:18,080
你能看见她把触手伸到鲨鱼的鳃里
you can see them coming through the gill, basically,

380
0:55:18,080 --> 0:55:20,360
堵住了鲨鱼的嘴 鲨鱼不能呼吸了
closed the mouth. The shark couldn't breathe,

381
0:55:20,360 --> 0:55:22,640
只能放她离开
and that's what enabled her to escape.

382
0:55:22,640 --> 0:55:25,480
我们亲眼见证整个过程
And just witnessing that whole thing was,

383
0:55:25,480 --> 0:55:28,920
那是生死攸关的时刻
you know, it was an incredibly intense moment.

384
0:55:30,400 --> 0:55:33,200
整个团队都因她逃走而松了一口气
The team are relieved by her escape.

385
0:55:45,920 --> 0:55:48,200
但当她在开阔的水域被发现时
But when caught out in the open,

386
0:55:48,200 --> 0:55:51,040
接下来的把戏更加令他们感到震惊
her next trick astonishes them even more.

387
0:55:54,760 --> 0:55:57,800
她将全身蜷缩起来
It lifted its arms and legs over its head,

388
0:55:57,800 --> 0:56:01,360
并把一些贝壳覆盖在身上
and, at the same time, pulled the shell material with it

389
0:56:01,360 --> 0:56:04,440
做成了这个超凡的盔甲
and created this extraordinary armoury.

390
0:56:06,280 --> 0:56:09,120
她武装好自己之后 那只鲨鱼
Octopus had armoured up and then, when that guy came

391
0:56:09,120 --> 0:56:12,280
自后面赶来 他能闻到一些气息
through from the back, he could kind of smell something.

392
0:56:12,280 --> 0:56:14,240
但没有看见章鱼
He's not seeing an octopus shape,

393
0:56:14,240 --> 0:56:17,560
而是看见这个奇怪的东西
he's seeing that strange armoury.

394
0:56:17,560 --> 0:56:20,000
接着他去碰撞这只章鱼
Then he was bumping the octopus,

395
0:56:20,000 --> 0:56:23,040
看着这只章鱼如何利用自己的盔甲
and it was just incredible to see how that octopus

396
0:56:23,040 --> 0:56:25,240
和智慧去战胜那只鲨鱼
outwitted that shark using the armour,

397
0:56:25,240 --> 0:56:27,320
简直不可思议
using all it's, it's knowledge,

398
0:56:27,320 --> 0:56:30,080
这是一场相当精彩的表演
it's just...absolutely phenomenal.

399
0:56:35,360 --> 0:56:38,160
她是个摇滚巨星 一个真正的摇滚巨星
She's a rock star, man. A proper little rock star.

400
0:56:39,920 --> 0:56:42,240
感谢克雷格和罗杰的奉献精神
Thanks to Craig's and Roger's dedication,

401
0:56:42,240 --> 0:56:46,920
现在科学界终于了解到了章鱼那不为人知的秘密
the octopuses' astonishing behaviours are now known to science.

402
0:56:49,240 --> 0:56:52,680
随着对海底森林的持续探索
What else might we find as we continue to explore

403
0:56:52,680 --> 0:56:56,160
我们还会发现什么呢
these fascinating undersea forests?

404
0:57:01,360 --> 0:57:04,160
下期蓝色星球Ⅱ
Next time on Blue Planet II...

405
0:57:04,160 --> 0:57:07,280
我们将与那些生活在两个世界交界处的生物们见面
we meet the creatures that live where two worlds collide...

406
0:57:10,160 --> 0:57:12,640
并探索它们将如何应对
..and discover how they cope with the demands

407
0:57:12,640 --> 0:57:15,320
海岸线的变化多端
of the ever-changing coasts.

